observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. require the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all properties of the Municipality and use the accounting records, if necessary, in the absence of complete records of PPE from the General Service Office and prepare the corresponding RPCPPE;
b. direct the (i) Municipal Accountant and the GSO to update the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, by providing adequate description of PPE in their respective reports/records to facilitate reconciliation; and (ii) thereafter, complete the reconciliation of both records, taking into consideration the deficiencies noted in audit;
c. require the GSO to (i) update the Property Acknowledgement Receipt; and (ii) initiate the proper disposal of all obsolete and unserviceable properties pursuant to Section 79 of P.D. No. 1445, Sections 379 to 381 of R.A. No. 7160, and in accordance with procedures provided by COA Circular No. 89-296 and Chapter 6 of Handbook on Property and Supply Management System (PSMS); and
d. instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to reconcile the PPE SLs with the CQRGPPAs and subsequently make the necessary adjustments/revisions on their respective reports, as appropriate.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. provide necessary appropriation to facilitate the titling of road lots/ROW of the Municipality;
b. instruct the Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (i) to facilitate the titling of the real properties; (ii) to validate and verify any third-party claims on the remaining road lots; (iii) thereafter, submit the legal documents to the Municipal Accountant for the recognition of the land component of the road/ROW in the books; and (iv) provide the total length of the road/ROW of the Municipality to the Municipal Accountant for disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements;
c. direct the Municipal Assessor to submit to the Audit Team the: (i) total land holdings of the Municipality of Bataraza; (ii) Copy of Tax Declaration; and (iii) Property Identification Map for verification and reference in audit; and
d. instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) recognize a zero salvage value for the depreciable component of the local road network system in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008 and accordingly make the necessary adjustments in the books; and (ii) disclose the impact of the changes in accounting policy, estimates and provide adequate disclosure of the Road Networks account in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the BAC Chairperson to (i) consolidate the PPMPs into an indicative APP before processing the procurement taking into consideration the noted deficiencies in audit; and (ii) discontinue the practice of splitting the procurement for fuel, oil and lubricants into smaller contracts to circumvent the necessity of competitive bidding;
b. consider reconstituting the composition of the Bids and Awards Committee Secretariat by designating additional members to perform the consolidation of the PPMPs into an indicative APP;
c. instruct the Municipal Engineering Office to submit a report on the utilization of the requisitioned fuel for the generator based on the power interruptions and discontinue the use of Driver’s Trip Tickets therefor; and
d. transfer the functions of fuel requisitions, monitoring and reporting from each department to the General Services Officer and designate a Gasoline Control Clerk from among the regular plantilla position of the GSO, otherwise fill in the vacant regular plantilla positions in the General Services Office to augment its manpower.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the HRMO to:
a. process only the payroll of employees with complete DTRs duly supported with necessary documents. Otherwise, return the DTRs to the concerned employees for compliance/submission of the required supporting documents;
b. formulate policy guidelines about personnel matters specifically on the daily time record of office-based and field-based employees; and the required attachments/documents in case of incomplete attendance or absence of time entries, among others;
c. submit the lacking required documents of terminal leave claims and henceforth, ensure that the required supporting documents for claims of terminal leaves are complete before forwarding the disbursement voucher to the Municipal Accountant; and
d. educate the employees on the proper preparation and filing of application for leave within the prescribed period set forth in CSC MC No. 41, s. 1998, and its amendments.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant check the completeness of supporting documents for terminal leave benefit, as enumerated in Section 5.13 of COA Circular No. 2012-001, before certifying/affixing her signature on the disbursement vouchers.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the HRMO and the Municipal Accountant to:
a. ensure that the ₱5,000.00 minimum take home pay of officials and employees is observed in compliance with the provisions of the GAA;
b. refrain from accommodating the payment of loan amortizations to bank and other lending institutions through payroll deduction if it will reduce the officials’ and employees’ monthly net take home pay below the minimum amount;
c. advise the concerned officials and employees to make direct payment to the bank or lending institution for any deficiency in the salary deducted loan amortizations; and
d. separate the payroll for RATA from the payment of salaries to ensure proper computation of the net take home pay and prepare only one payroll for RATA for all authorized recipients per month to save on cost and time in preparing too many JEVs.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor (i) designates an SDO, different from the DO, who will handle disbursements for special purpose/time-bound activities or events; (ii) limit the grant of cash advances within the authorized maximum cash accountability covered by the approved amount of bond of the DO; and (iii) file request for authority to write-off dormant accounts from COA duly supported with necessary papers/documents as embodied in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;

DO/SDO refrain transferring his cash advance or accountability to another accountable officer;

Municipal Accountant compute the total amount deducted from the salaries Of Ms. Aurora Laxamana, Local Revenue Collecting Officer I, and serve a written notice demanding cash advances as mandated In COA Circular No. 2012-004, otherwise, cause the suspension/withholding of her salary upon failure to settle her accountabilities; and

Municipal Mayor and the Municipal Accountant strictly observe the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1992 on the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.
